NYT of August 15, 1915 
  <a href="http://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F40817FC385B17738DDDAC0994D0405B858DF1D3" rel="nofollow">query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F40817FC385B17738...</a>
reported that &quot;Miss Detroit, the hydroplane designed by C.C. Smith of Algonac, Michigan, and owned by the Detroit Power Boat Association won the first leg of the series of three races for the Gold Challenge Cup over the thirty mile Manhasset Bay course of Fort Washington yesterday afternoon.  Badly away at the start she covered the course in 42 minutes 41 3-5 seconds, or at the rate of 48.49-statute miles per hour, or 42.17 knots, or nautical miles.&quot;

<a href="http://www.robbreportcollection.com/The-Gentlemens-Club?mpid=1" rel="nofollow">www.robbreportcollection.com/The-Gentlemens-Club?mpid=1</a> says,
&quot;That all changed in 1915 when Christopher Columbus Smith, the founder of the mahogany powerboat manufacturer Chris-Craft, built Miss Detroit, a hydroplaning boat that reached 60 mph and claimed the winner’s trophy that year.&quot;
